'''Ryukyū Limestone''' (ryūkyū sekkai gan) is a [[Limestone]] [[Stratigraphy]] widely distributed throughout the {{ill|Southwest Islands|ja|南西諸島|qq=draft|qq=draft}}. It was formed during the {{ill|Pleistocene|ja|更新世|qq=draft|qq=draft}} by the action of {{ill|Coral Reefs|ja|サンゴ礁|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, and was named in 1925 ({{ill|Taishō|ja|大正|qq=draft|qq=draft}} 14) by {{ill|Yabe Nagakatsu|ja|矢部長克|qq=draft|qq=draft}} and {{ill|Hasawa Masashirō|ja|半沢正四郎|qq=draft|qq=draft}}.

== Distribution ==
It is widely distributed from the central to the southern parts of the Southwest Islands, and in particular in {{ill|Okinawa Prefecture|ja|沖縄県|qq=draft|qq=draft}} it covers about 30 {{ill|Percent|ja|パーセント|qq=draft|qq=draft}} of the land. Its maximum thickness reaches up to 150 {{ill|Meters|ja|メートル|qq=draft|qq=draft}}.

;Regions where Ryukyū Limestone is Exposed
{{ill|Kagoshima Prefecture|ja|鹿児島県|qq=draft|qq=draft}}
: {{ill|Takarajima|ja|宝島|qq=draft|qq=draft}} (northern limit of distribution), {{ill|Kikaijima|ja|喜界島|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, {{ill|Okinaraibu Island|ja|沖永良部島|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, {{ill|Yoron Island|ja|与論島|qq=draft|qq=draft}}
{{ill|Okinawa Prefecture|ja|沖縄県|qq=draft|qq=draft}}
: {{ill|Iejima|ja|伊江島|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, {{ill|Sesokojima|ja|瀬底島|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, {{ill|Kouri Island|ja|古宇利島|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, {{ill|Tsukanezima|ja|津堅島|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, {{ill|Awakuni Island|ja|粟国島|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, central and southern parts of {{ill|Okinawa Island|ja|沖縄島|qq=draft|qq=draft}}
: {{ill|Kitadaitōjima|ja|北大東島|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, {{ill|Minamidaitōjima|ja|南大東島|qq=draft|qq=draft}}
: {{ill|Miyakojima|ja|宮古島|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, {{ill|Irabujima|ja|伊良部島|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, {{ill|Tarama Island|ja|多良間島|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, {{ill|Minamijima (Tarama)|ja|水納島|qq=draft|qq=draft}}
: Southern parts of {{ill|Ishigaki Island|ja|石垣島|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, {{ill|Taketomishima|ja|竹富島|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, {{ill|Kuroshima|ja|黒島|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, {{ill|Hateruma Island|ja|波照間島|qq=draft|qq=draft}}

Because coral reefs form in shallow seas, the presence of Ryukyū Limestone indicates that these areas were near sea level at the time of formation. For example, near the {{ill|Kerama Islands|ja|慶良間諸島|qq=draft|qq=draft}} between {{ill|Okinawa Island|ja|沖縄島|qq=draft|qq=draft}} and {{ill|Kumejima|ja|久米島|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, Ryukyū Limestone is found at about 80 meters below sea level, indicating that subsidence occurred in that region.<ref>{{Cite web|url= http://www.pref.osaka.lg.jp/midorikikaku/toshiryokka/hyakusenn.html|title=Osaka Green 100 Selection|publisher=Osaka Prefecture|accessdate=2016-12-23|language=ja}}</ref>

== Topography ==
The Ryukyū Limestone forms a plateau that rises on top of the underlying {{ill|Shimajiri Mudstone|ja|島尻層泥岩|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, which is the basement rock of the Southwest Islands, and is surrounded by steep slopes. Numerous {{ill|Karst Caves|ja|鍾乳洞|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, numbering in the hundreds such as {{ill|Gyokusendō|ja|玉泉洞|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, are distributed throughout the region. Unlike typical limestone formations where depressions known as “{{ill|Doline|ja|ドリーネ|qq=draft|qq=draft}}” are common, the Ryukyū Limestone area is characterized by many embankment-like hills.<ref>{{Cite book|title=日本の地形7 九州・南西諸島|publisher=Tokyo University Press|year=2001|author=町田洋 et al.|isbn=4-13-064717-2|language=ja}}</ref>

== Characteristics and Uses ==
[[File:Kinjocho ishidatami-michi Shuri Naha04n4272.jpg|thumb|200px|[[Kinjochō Ishidatami-michi]] – a stone-paved road made of Ryukyū Limestone]]
Ryukyū Limestone contains numerous {{ill|Pores|ja|気孔|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, which allow substantial infiltration of groundwater. At the boundary with the less permeable {{ill|Shimajiri Mudstone|ja|島尻層泥岩|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, many springs are found. In {{ill|Miyakojima|ja|宮古島|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, this property has been utilized in the construction of {{ill|Fukuri Dam|ja|福里ダム|qq=draft|qq=draft}} and other underground dams.

Since ancient times in {{ill|Okinawa Prefecture|ja|沖縄県|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, Ryukyū Limestone has been used as a building material. It was employed in constructing stone-paved roads and stone walls surrounding houses, and was used in the construction of fortifications such as {{ill|Shuri Castle|ja|首里城|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, various {{ill|Gusuku|ja|グスク|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, and imperial tombs like {{ill|Gyokuryō|ja|玉陵|qq=draft|qq=draft}}. Today, it is still used as a building material for stone walls and {{ill|Kikkō-bako|ja|亀甲墓|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, as well as being mixed with asphalt as aggregate for road paving. However, stone pavements made of Ryukyū Limestone become very slippery when wet.

== Types ==
The types of limestone vary according to the water depth of the sea in which they were formed. Because the substrate of the Southwest Islands has repeatedly experienced uplift and subsidence, and due to fluctuations in the sea level, various types of limestone can be observed in different regions and periods.<ref name="R01">{{Cite book|title=沖縄の自然 地形と地質|publisher=Hirugisha|year=1990|author=松田伸也 and Zenko Zemma|language=ja}}</ref>
; Coral Limestone
: Limestone rich in fossils of {{ill|Reef-building Coral|ja|造礁サンゴ|qq=draft|qq=draft}}.
; Calcareous Algae Nodular Limestone
: Limestone abundant in {{ill|Calcareous Algae Nodules|ja|石灰藻球|qq=draft|qq=draft}}.
; Cycloperrius Limestone
: Limestone containing large numbers of foraminifera such as {{ill|Cycloperrius|ja|サイクロペリウス|qq=draft|qq=draft}} and {{ill|Opacirina|ja|オパキュリナ|qq=draft|qq=draft}}.
; Clastic Limestone
: Limestone containing many fragments of foraminifera, corals, algae, and bryozoans.

