The Ryukyū Limestone forms a plateau that rises on top of the underlying {{ill|Shimajiri Mudstone|ja|島尻層泥岩|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Shimajiri Mudstone|qq=}}, which is the basement rock of the Southwest Islands, and is surrounded by steep slopes. Numerous {{ill|Karst Caves|ja|鍾乳洞|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Karst Caves|qq=}}, numbering in the hundreds such as {{ill|Gyokusendō|ja|玉泉洞|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Gyokusendō|qq=}}, are distributed throughout the region. Unlike typical limestone formations where depressions known as “{{ill|Doline|ja|ドリーネ|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Doline|qq=}}” are common, the Ryukyū Limestone area is characterized by many embankment-like hills.<ref>{{Cite book|title=日本の地形7 九州・南西諸島|publisher=Tokyo University Press|year=2001|author=町田洋 et al.|isbn=4-13-064717-2|language=ja}}</ref>

== Characteristics and Uses ==
[[File:Kinjocho ishidatami-michi Shuri Naha04n4272.jpg|thumb|200px|[[Kinjochō Ishidatami-michi]] – a stone-paved road made of Ryukyū Limestone]]
Ryukyū Limestone contains numerous {{ill|Pores|ja|気孔|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Pores|qq=}}, which allow substantial infiltration of groundwater. At the boundary with the less permeable {{ill|Shimajiri Mudstone|ja|島尻層泥岩|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Shimajiri Mudstone|qq=}}, many springs are found. In {{ill|Miyakojima|ja|宮古島|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Miyakojima|qq=}}, this property has been utilized in the construction of {{ill|Fukuri Dam|ja|福里ダム|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Fukuri Dam|qq=}} and other underground dams.

Since ancient times in {{ill|Okinawa Prefecture|ja|沖縄県|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Okinawa Prefecture|qq=}}, Ryukyū Limestone has been used as a building material. It was employed in constructing stone-paved roads and stone walls surrounding houses, and was used in the construction of fortifications such as {{ill|Shuri Castle|ja|首里城|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Shuri Castle|qq=}}, various {{ill|Gusuku|ja|グスク|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Gusuku|qq=}}, and imperial tombs like {{ill|Gyokuryō|ja|玉陵|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Gyokuryō|qq=}}. Today, it is still used as a building material for stone walls and {{ill|Kikkō-bako|ja|亀甲墓|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kikkō-bako|qq=}}, as well as being mixed with asphalt as aggregate for road paving. However, stone pavements made of Ryukyū Limestone become very slippery when wet.

== Types ==
The types of limestone vary according to the water depth of the sea in which they were formed. Because the substrate of the Southwest Islands has repeatedly experienced uplift and subsidence, and due to fluctuations in the sea level, various types of limestone can be observed in different regions and periods.<ref name="R01">{{Cite book|title=沖縄の自然 地形と地質|publisher=Hirugisha|year=1990|author=松田伸也 and Zenko Zemma|language=ja}}</ref>
; Coral Limestone
: Limestone rich in fossils of {{ill|Reef-building Coral|ja|造礁サンゴ|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Reef-building Coral|qq=}}.
; Calcareous Algae Nodular Limestone
: Limestone abundant in {{ill|Calcareous Algae Nodules|ja|石灰藻球|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Calcareous Algae Nodules|qq=}}.
; Cycloperrius Limestone
: Limestone containing large numbers of foraminifera such as {{ill|Cycloperrius|ja|サイクロペリウス|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Cycloperrius|qq=}} and {{ill|Opacirina|ja|オパキュリナ|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Opacirina|qq=}}.
; Clastic Limestone
: Limestone containing many fragments of foraminifera, corals, algae, and bryozoans.

