'''Ryukyū Limestone''' (ryūkyū sekkai gan) is a [[Limestone]] [[Stratigraphy]] widely distributed throughout the [[:en:Ryukyu Islands|Southwest Islands]]. It was formed during the [[:en:Pleistocene|Pleistocene]] by the action of [[:en:Coral reef|Coral Reefs]], and was named in 1925 ([[:en:Taishō era|Taishō]] 14) by [[:en:Hisakatsu Yabe|Yabe Nagakatsu]] and {{ill|Hasawa Masashirō|ja|半沢正四郎|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Hasawa Masashirō|qq=}}.
== Distribution == It is widely distributed from the central to the southern parts of the Southwest Islands, and in particular in [[:en:Okinawa Prefecture|Okinawa Prefecture]] it covers about 30 [[:en:Percentage|Percent]] of the land. Its maximum thickness reaches up to 150 [[:en:Metre|Meters]].
;Regions where Ryukyū Limestone is Exposed [[:en:Kagoshima Prefecture|Kagoshima Prefecture]] : [[:en:Treasure Island|Takarajima]] (northern limit of distribution), [[:en:Kikaijima|Kikaijima]], [[:en:Okinoerabujima|Okinaraibu Island]], [[:en:Yoronjima|Yoron Island]] [[:en:Okinawa Prefecture|Okinawa Prefecture]] : [[:en:Iejima|Iejima]], [[:en:Sesoko Island|Sesokojima]], {{ill|Kouri Island|ja|古宇利島|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kouri Island|qq=}}, [[:en:Tsuken Island|Tsukanezima]], [[:en:Aguni Island|Awakuni Island]], central and southern parts of {{ill|Okinawa Island|ja|沖縄島|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Okinawa Island|qq=}} : [[:en:Kitadaitōjima|Kitadaitōjima]], [[:en:Minamidaitōjima|Minamidaitōjima]] : [[:en:Miyako Island|Miyakojima]], [[:en:Irabu Island|Irabujima]], {{ill|Tarama Island|ja|多良間島|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Tarama Island|qq=}}, [[:en:Minnajima|Minamijima (Tarama)]] : Southern parts of [[:en:Ishigaki Island|Ishigaki Island]], [[:en:Taketomi Island|Taketomishima]], [[:en:Kuroshima|Kuroshima]], [[:en:Hateruma|Hateruma Island]]
Because coral reefs form in shallow seas, the presence of Ryukyū Limestone indicates that these areas were near sea level at the time of formation. For example, near the [[:en:Kerama Islands|Kerama Islands]] between {{ill|Okinawa Island|ja|沖縄島|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Okinawa Island|qq=}} and [[:en:Kume Island|Kumejima]], Ryukyū Limestone is found at about 80 meters below sea level, indicating that subsidence occurred in that region.<ref>{{Cite web|url= http://www.pref.osaka.lg.jp/midorikikaku/toshiryokka/hyakusenn.html|title=Osaka Green 100 Selection|publisher=Osaka Prefecture|accessdate=2016-12-23|language=ja}}</ref>
== Topography == The Ryukyū Limestone forms a plateau that rises on top of the underlying {{ill|Shimajiri Mudstone|ja|島尻層泥岩|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Shimajiri Mudstone|qq=}}, which is the basement rock of the Southwest Islands, and is surrounded by steep slopes. Numerous [[:en:Solutional cave|Karst Caves]], numbering in the hundreds such as {{ill|Gyokusendō|ja|玉泉洞|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Gyokusendō|qq=}}, are distributed throughout the region. Unlike typical limestone formations where depressions known as “{{ill|Doline|ja|ドリーネ|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Doline|qq=}}” are common, the Ryukyū Limestone area is characterized by many embankment-like hills.<ref>{{Cite book|title=日本の地形7 九州・南西諸島|publisher=Tokyo University Press|year=2001|author=町田洋 et al.|isbn=4-13-064717-2|language=ja}}</ref>
== Characteristics and Uses == [[File:Kinjocho ishidatami-michi Shuri Naha04n4272.jpg|thumb|200px|[[Kinjochō Ishidatami-michi]] – a stone-paved road made of Ryukyū Limestone]] Ryukyū Limestone contains numerous [[:en:Stoma|Pores]], which allow substantial infiltration of groundwater. At the boundary with the less permeable {{ill|Shimajiri Mudstone|ja|島尻層泥岩|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Shimajiri Mudstone|qq=}}, many springs are found. In [[:en:Miyako Island|Miyakojima]], this property has been utilized in the construction of [[:en:Fukuzato Underground Dam|Fukuri Dam]] and other underground dams.
Since ancient times in [[:en:Okinawa Prefecture|Okinawa Prefecture]], Ryukyū Limestone has been used as a building material. It was employed in constructing stone-paved roads and stone walls surrounding houses, and was used in the construction of fortifications such as [[:en:Shuri Castle|Shuri Castle]], various [[:en:Gusuku|Gusuku]], and imperial tombs like [[:en:Tamaudun|Gyokuryō]]. Today, it is still used as a building material for stone walls and [[:en:Turtleback tomb|Kikkō-bako]], as well as being mixed with asphalt as aggregate for road paving. However, stone pavements made of Ryukyū Limestone become very slippery when wet.
== Types == The types of limestone vary according to the water depth of the sea in which they were formed. Because the substrate of the Southwest Islands has repeatedly experienced uplift and subsidence, and due to fluctuations in the sea level, various types of limestone can be observed in different regions and periods.<ref name="R01">{{Cite book|title=沖縄の自然 地形と地質|publisher=Hirugisha|year=1990|author=松田伸也 and Zenko Zemma|language=ja}}</ref> ; Coral Limestone : Limestone rich in fossils of [[:en:Hermatypic coral|Reef-building Coral]]. ; Calcareous Algae Nodular Limestone : Limestone abundant in {{ill|Calcareous Algae Nodules|ja|石灰藻球|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Calcareous Algae Nodules|qq=}}. ; Cycloperrius Limestone : Limestone containing large numbers of foraminifera such as {{ill|Cycloperrius|ja|サイクロペリウス|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Cycloperrius|qq=}} and {{ill|Opacirina|ja|オパキュリナ|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Opacirina|qq=}}. ; Clastic Limestone : Limestone containing many fragments of foraminifera, corals, algae, and bryozoans.
