'''Ryukyū Limestone''' (ryūkyū sekkai gan) is a [[:en:Limestone|Limestone]] [[Stratigraphy]] widely distributed throughout the [[:en:Ryukyu Islands|Southwest Islands]]. It was formed during the [[:en:Pleistocene|Pleistocene]] by the action of [[:en:Coral reef|Coral Reefs]], and was named in 1925 ([[:en:Taishō era|Taishō]] 14) by [[:en:Hisakatsu Yabe|Yabe Nagakatsu]] and {{ill|Hasawa Masashirō|ja|半沢正四郎|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Hasawa Masashirō|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki link invalid}}.
== Distribution == It is widely distributed from the central to the southern parts of the Southwest Islands, and in particular in [[:en:Okinawa Prefecture|Okinawa Prefecture]] it covers about 30 [[:en:Percentage|Percent]] of the land. Its maximum thickness reaches up to 150 [[:en:Metre|Meters]].
;Regions where Ryukyū Limestone is Exposed [[:en:Kagoshima Prefecture|Kagoshima Prefecture]] : [[:en:Treasure Island|Takarajima]] (northern limit of distribution), [[:en:Kikaijima|Kikaijima]], [[:en:Okinoerabujima|Okinaraibu Island]], [[:en:Yoronjima|Yoron Island]] [[:en:Okinawa Prefecture|Okinawa Prefecture]] : [[:en:Iejima|Iejima]], [[:en:Sesoko Island|Sesokojima]], {{ill|Kouri Island|ja|古宇利島|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kouri Island|qq=}}, [[:en:Tsuken Island|Tsukanezima]], [[:en:Aguni Island|Awakuni Island]], central and southern parts of {{ill|Okinawa Island|ja|沖縄島|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Okinawa Island|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki redirects to 沖縄本島}} : [[:en:Kitadaitōjima|Kitadaitōjima]], [[:en:Minamidaitōjima|Minamidaitōjima]] : [[:en:Miyako Island|Miyakojima]], [[:en:Irabu Island|Irabujima]], {{ill|Tarama Island|ja|多良間島|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Tarama Island|qq=}}, [[:en:Minnajima|Minamijima (Tarama)]] : Southern parts of [[:en:Ishigaki Island|Ishigaki Island]], [[:en:Taketomi Island|Taketomishima]], [[:en:Kuroshima|Kuroshima]], [[:en:Hateruma|Hateruma Island]]
Because coral reefs form in shallow seas, the presence of Ryukyū Limestone indicates that these areas were near sea level at the time of formation. For example, near the [[:en:Kerama Islands|Kerama Islands]] between {{ill|Okinawa Island|ja|沖縄島|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Okinawa Island|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki redirects to 沖縄本島}} and [[:en:Kume Island|Kumejima]], Ryukyū Limestone is found at about 80 meters below sea level, indicating that subsidence occurred in that region.<ref>{{Cite web|url= http://www.pref.osaka.lg.jp/midorikikaku/toshiryokka/hyakusenn.html|title=Osaka Green 100 Selection|publisher=Osaka Prefecture|accessdate=2016-12-23|language=ja}}</ref>
